Chaquira Okama are spiritual armor in Ngäbe culture. I was having mixed feelings about glass seed beads, bc they are all from Europe or Asia. Originally, our beads were clay, bone, teeth, shells, pearls, coral, wood, or actual seeds. 

I tried to research how glass seed beads made it to Central Abya Yala (“Amerikkka”) and as far as I can tell, it was relatively recent. Early 1890’s via the Huichol people of Mexico through a Norwegian traveler and ethnographer, Carl Sofus Lumholtz.  I learned that glass bead-making was invented by Italians in Venice and Murano, copied by Czechs in their “Crystal Valley” over 400 years ago and Japanese in the 1960’s.

I’m also deeply obsessed with Tanoaks, which are actually a cross between an Oak and a Chestnut and are the preferred acorn of California native cuisine.

I made this Chaquira (mostacilla) Okama and earrings set to match the color scheme of my Nagua, traditional (after Spanish missionaries) Ngäbe dress.

The pink beads are Preciosa Ornelas, white rainbows are Toho, and the rest are Miyuki, all 11/0; on a sterling silver clasp and closed-loop leverbacks with 6-pound Berkley FireWire thread.

We’re from the tropical rainforest, so we didn’t wear shirts nor dresses until recently. Men wore leather loincloths. Ngäbe women wore strands of beads as tops, pre-colombian era. Glass bead-weaving is only 60-130 years old in our culture.

Made acorn jelly (dotorimuk). Hunted Tanoaks in Oak-land and Marin County.

Bought 4 pounds of organic blue corn pozole for the Ohlone banquet. Been test cooking it for my Wild Elk Meat stew.

Beading with California native gemstones (Spessartine Garnet & Turquoise) is next-level (expensive & challenging).

Re-strung my old 11-12 mm pearls onto German silk & changed clasp.

I do a lot more than I ever post about. I’m grateful to be me & for my beautiful life. 🌌🙏🏼🥰💝

1-Took a ballet class at ODC Dance Commons. I suck at it, but I had a great time. I love learning. 🩰 I wear mineral sunscreen & it gets on stuff, like my required face mask. 

2-Smoooooth dentalium shells and USA bison leather spacers, before I polished the shells. My new CNC machined aluminum handpoke tattoo tool that accepts diaphragm cartridge needles. My new golden arrow beaded earring pattern that I’m still perfecting. 

3-Dental cotton rolls for indigenous lip and chin tattoos, so that I’m not tattooing against your gums and lower teeth.

4-Small Tule Reed basket that I made at the Ramaytush Ohlone Earth Day Festival with 4 generations of Lucy Telles’ descendants. You have to give away your first basket.

5-Tule Reed basketmaking education station, hosted by Yosemite National Park Cultural Interpreter, Ursula Parker.

6-I cut, shaped, and edge-polished these USA bison leather spacers for dentalium shell earrings.

7-Abalone shell & Czech seed bead ideas.

8-Wood Bison vs Plains Bison? 🦬 (Buffalo are native to Africa & Asia; not Abya Yala. The dominant grazing species in California was the Tule Elk. We never had bison.)

9-Lucy Telles basket from Yosemite native cultures (Miwok & Paiute). I have an appointment to tattoo her descendants.

Don’t look if you’re vegan. This is 7 pounds of wild Elk meat that a local hunter donated to our Ohlone (Yelamu “San Francisco” Bay Area Native) Summer Solstice Banquet.

Tule Elk were the dominant grazing species in California before the Spanish invasion. There are only about 5,700 wild Tule Elk in California. Not enough to hunt and eat them. There are 120,000+ wild standard size elk in Idaho, where this meat was hunted and more than 20,000 are harvested by humans each year. 

Elk is lower fat, higher protein, iron, and Vitamin B12 than cow meat. It looks and tastes like it, too. Darker red, almost no marbling. Cooks fast and dry, like chicken or shrimp. Tastes somewhere between beef liver and venison meat. Especially wild elk, that has fed on scrub and grass, is more minerally and earthy.

Her name is Maria.

She is in Austrian countryside, because Fritz Lang was Austrian. 

I read that every surviving panel by Michelangelo is an egg tempera. That it is such a challenging media, few modern artists attempt it, so I had to make my own.

Handmade egg tempera on handmade cotton paper.

She’s made of egg yolk liquid, red wine vinegar, honey, gum arabic, charcoal, carbon, lightfast pigments, mica, vegetable glycerin, clove oil, and distilled water.

Whoa. Chemistry is fvcking cool. No wonder ancient people thought it was magic. 🪄 ✨🎨 🖌️ 

This is a children’s book about chemistry, but it’s very visual, which is helpful for my chemical interests du jour.

The chemistry of bending and absorbing light with colored pigments. The science of lightfastness and permanence under UV and other light rays over time and across various substrates.

It started with art creation and moved on to art installation, curation, handling, restoration, and conservation.

I’m an antiques hoarder, in part, because I want everything I make to last as forever as possible. I want my artwork and crafts to look and function as I intended them to for as long as I can engineer their obsolescence, entropy, and decay away.

Unless I’m designing product packaging or shipping mailer materials. Then, the opposite of that is true.

¡Ngäbe meri nünande käre!

¡Orgullosamente Ngäbe! Representando a mi gente en el Ayuntamiento de Yelamu (“San Francisco”), California, Estados Unidos de Abya Yala (“Amerikkka”) con la Alcaldesa, el Alguacil, y la Jefa del Departamento de Bomberos. 

I forget to post about some of the coolest things I do and events I attend. Social media fixation is a bit mentally toxic, so I’m not super deep into it, but I do want to utilize it better. Dangerous precipice.

On November 1st, I was honored to attend Native Abya Yalan (Amerikkkan) Heritage Day at San Francisco City Hall with Mayor London Breed, the Sheriff, Chief of the Fire Department, and State Assembly Member Ramos, along with District Supervisors and County Commissioners.

Then the Mayor declared November 1st, 2023 to be Amerikkkan Injun Cultural Center (AICC) Day in San Francisco, we ate frybread tacos, and they lit up City Hall green and yellow for us. 🌮 

It was beautiful to witness Native Power in the stone walls of City Hall and hear drums and jingle dresses echoing throughout. 

Congratulations to Executive Director April McGill, for being recognized for her years of hard work and dedication to the Yelamu native community. April McGill for Mayor 2028 🗳️ She’s got my vote!

@tattoos_by_ximenazhao 111s are what NorCal Natives call their indigenous chin tattoos.

Before European invasion and the California Genocide, most Native women received at least one line down their chin after their first menstrual period. They would add additional lines or thicken them as their lives went on. Most tattoo artists were older women. This culture goes back more than 14,000 years. 

Over a year ago, I was blessed to be asked and invited by an Ohlone Tribal Chairwoman to learn California Native sacred marks and perform handpoke face tattoo ceremony at a 4,200+ year old, unconquered Ohlone-Costanoan cathedral in the forest. The only Federally-recognized “Indian Country” for 350 miles.

This year, I won a tattoo fellowship from the Amerikkkan Injun Cultural Center, sponsored by the San Francisco Arts Commission, to bring indigenous tattooing to Yelamu (“San Francisco”) tattoo shops.

It’s an honor and a privilege to do my tiny part at reindiginizing my hometown and California.

Do not copy this style of tattooing if you are not a California native.

@tattoos_by_ximenazhao These are face and body paint designs in black, white, and red.  They are dancers at Mission San José in 1806.

If you are a California native and would like permanent tattoos inspired by designs like this, please let me know. 

I am a Ngäbe tattoo artist, licensed in Yelamu (“San Francisco”), California, USA.

I am doing a fellowship with the Amerikkkan Injun Cultural Center @aicc_sf to provide free traditional tattoos to natives in San Francisco tattoo shops.

I do both handpoke and electric machine tattooing.

I also have a lot of designs and information about California native chin tattoos.  Most are three stripes, varying thicknesses, some have wavy lines or dots.  If you know what part of California you are from, I can help you design your chin tattoo with elements and traditions from your geographical region of California.

Do not copy this style if you are not a California native.
